; Use the npm v6-style peer dependency resolver.
;
; Why: most of our transitive React tree (excalidraw internals, @floating-ui,
; @radix-ui, etc.) still declares `peer react@^18`, but we ship React 19.
; Under npm v7+ default behavior this floods every install with
; `npm warn ERESOLVE overriding peer dependency` lines that we can't fix
; upstream. legacy-peer-deps tells npm to skip auto-installing & enforcing
; peer deps (the npm v6 contract), which silences those warnings without
; changing what actually ends up in node_modules — our root deps,
; `overrides`, and lockfile still control resolution.
;
; If you ever audit peers manually, run:
;   npm install --no-legacy-peer-deps --dry-run
legacy-peer-deps=true
